
Reuben Houston is steadied by the conviction of his own truth. His eyes do not dart with embarrassment. His spirit is not shattered by circumstance. Four months after an arrest on drug charges and a premature end to a promising senior football season at Georgia Tech, Houston is whole and hopeful, he told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution on Monday. His reputation is tarnished by what he called an "exaggerated" story of his involvement in a federal drug case stemming from Fresno, Calif. But he does not hang his head with shame or guilt, he said. "It's not embarrassing or painful," Houston said. "Angry would probably be the right word. But not angry at the situation, more at myself for putting myself in this situation. It knocked the wind out of me. 

